 The drought of 1988 hit hardest in the upper Midwest _ perhaps nowhere harder than in North Dakota.
 More disaster relief aid went there than to any other state.
 The third story in a four-part series, ``Cashing In on the Drought,'' examines how the $3.9 billion disaster aid program helped farmers most in need.
 Carl Grindberg survived the drought with a $45,000 dose of federal aid.
 What I'm saying is, the farmer got the money directly, but indirectly a lot of others benefited.'' The 1988 drought relief program poured more than $400 million into North Dakota, the nation's most agriculturally dependent state.
